  "text": "Note that A ∈ R 2n×4 is a function of {u i , v i , P i } N i=1 , as specified in Equations (8) and [CITATION_1] . We refer to A as the DLT matrix. These equations define x up to a scale factor, and we seek a non-zero solution. In the absence of noise, Equation (10) admits a unique non-trivial solution, corresponding to the 3D intersection of the camera rays passing by each 2D observation u i (i.e. matrix A does not have full rank). However, considering noisy 2D point observations such as the ones predicted by a neural network, Equation (10) does not admit solutions, thus we have to seek for an approximate one. A common choice, known as the Direct Linear Transform (DLT) method [CITATION_2] , proposes the following relaxed version of Equation (10):",
